    "body": "I started noodling a lot about this... Here's the main points of my thinking.\n- We can't rely on run_tests, as #5573 and #4878 are proving that people are willing to run the tests using `make tests`. I'd even argue that tests are better off being self-enclosed, and not rely on external things (python interpreter, python script, altered root certificates via environment variable)\n- Right now, https?cli_test are the only two tests that require an external python interpreter to properly run.\n- We could theoretically make `make test` run `run_tests -lc,c++ -c$CONFIG`, but we'd push more and more towards rendering python necessary - and making the tests not self-enclosed (think Windows, probably ?)\n- We originally migrated from using google.com to a python server to alleviate the possible redirect issues. Did we care about network connectivity ? I'm not sure.\n\nHow about we change our nginx configuration for grpc-testing.appspot.com to add a static hello world to a known test url, so that we can use https?://grpc-testing.appspot.com/httpcli_test as an actual testing target.\n\nPros:\n- No longer require an external python script (which sometime won't go down if an assert fails btw, hence leaking a bit)\n- Reduces the dependency burden for people willing to run our C-core tests on their machines (aka, the canonical `make test`).\n- No longer require bogus root certificates, which would've avoided #4878, and would prevent further issues related to using a side-loaded external file into a test.\n- Test can then run on all platforms, not just Linux.\n\nCons:\n- Require an actual internet connection.\n- If GCP goes down, the test fails.\n"
  },
